    "title": "bip360: disallow depth-zero script trees in P2MR",
    "user": {
      "login": "conduition",
      "id": 130806907,
      "node_id": "U_kgDOB8v0ew",
      "avatar_url": "https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/130806907?v=4",
      "gravatar_id": "",
      "url": "https://api.github.com/users/conduition",
      "html_url": "https://github.com/conduition",
      "followers_url": "https://api.github.com/users/conduition/followers",
      "following_url": "https://api.github.com/users/conduition/following%7B/other_user%7D",
      "gists_url": "https://api.github.com/users/conduition/gists%7B/gist_id%7D",
      "starred_url": "https://api.github.com/users/conduition/starred%7B/owner%7D%7B/repo%7D",
      "subscriptions_url": "https://api.github.com/users/conduition/subscriptions",
      "organizations_url": "https://api.github.com/users/conduition/orgs",
      "repos_url": "https://api.github.com/users/conduition/repos",
      "events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/conduition/events%7B/privacy%7D",
      "received_events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/conduition/received_events",
      "type": "User",
      "site_admin": false,
      "name": null,
      "patch_url": null
    },
    "body": "This changes the validation rules of BIP360 to prevent users from spending script trees of depth zero - those with a single leaf script.\r\n\r\nThis change is motivated by constructive critiques of P2MR which highlight the regressive use-cases which depth-zero script trees seem to incentivize.\r\n\r\nhttps://groups.google.com/g/bitcoindev/c/p8AVEmAtWdA\r\n\r\nThis specifically includes disincentivizing the use of a PQ script. With depth-zero script trees in play, users may have incentive to omit a PQ leaf script from their P2MR address to save 32 bytes of witness data when spending with Schnorr.\r\n\r\nWe also must consider the same incentive for multi-party transaction protocol authors, who may be incentivized to omit a cooperative leaf script to save 32 bytes off the witness of the non-cooperative script.\r\n\r\nAfter this change, P2MR's privacy profile is much more well aligned with that of P2TR: Every user must pay for at least two spending paths anyway, so it encourages everyone to make use of both of them if possible/applicable, whether for cooperative spending path or for a PQ leaf. We thus create ambiguity to on-chain observers: is this a cooperative spend of a multi-party protocol? or just a single-signer wallet with a sibling PQ leaf script?",
